Today we remember and reflect on the events of September 11, 2001. We typically share a statement and a moment of silence with our school community at 8:46am each school year. This year we want to let you know that you are all in our thoughts and the people affected by the events of 9/11 are in our thoughts. ğŸ’™ğŸ’›ğŸ¾

On September 11, 2001, 19 militants associated with the Islamic extremist group al Qaeda hijacked four airplanes and carried out suicide attacks against targets in the United States. Two of the planes were flown into the twin towers of the World Trade Center in New York City, a third plane hit the Pentagon just outside Washington, D.C., and the fourth plane crashed in a field in Shanksville, Pennsylvania. Almost 3,000 people were killed during the 9/11 terrorist attacks, which triggered major U.S. initiatives to combat terrorism and defined the presidency of George W. Bush.
Read more at: https://www.history.com/topics/21st-century/9-11-attacks

Labor Day, the first Monday in September, is a creation of the labor movement and is dedicated to the social and economic achievements of American workers. It constitutes a yearly national tribute to the contributions workers have made to the strength, prosperity, and well-being of our country.
>>>>>>> master

The first Labor Day holiday was celebrated on Tuesday, September 5, 1882, in New York City, in accordance with the plans of the Central Labor Union. The Central Labor Union held its second Labor Day holiday just a year later, on September 5, 1883.

By 1894, 23 more states had adopted the holiday, and on June 28, 1894, President Grover Cleveland signed a law making the first Monday in September of each year a national holiday.

Learn more at https://www.dol.gov/general/laborday/history
text:
Labor Day, the first Monday in September, is a creation of the labor movement and is dedicated to the social and economic achievements of American workers. It constitutes a yearly national tribute to the contributions workers have made to the strength, prosperity, and well-being of our country.

The first Labor Day holiday was celebrated on Tuesday, September 5, 1882, in New York City, in accordance with the plans of the Central Labor Union. The Central Labor Union held its second Labor Day holiday just a year later, on September 5, 1883.

By 1894, 23 more states had adopted the holiday, and on June 28, 1894, President Grover Cleveland signed a law making the first Monday in September of each year a national holiday.

Learn more at https://www.dol.gov/general/laborday/history

North Atlantic States Regional Council of Carpenters
July 31 at 8:12 AM Â·

Friday is for the Membersâ€¼ï¸

Samantha chose to be a union carpenter because she liked building things since she was little. In high school, she went to Tri-County RVTHS and ended up in the Carpentry program, where she did Career Connections. It helped her prepare for the union and she received a one year credit for the apprentice program. She went on a field trip to visit the training center, where they taught the students about the carpentry apprenticeship program, the benefits, and that is what made her decide that she wanted to join the Carpenters Union.

She has only been in the Union for a few weeks now because she just graduated high school, but so far it has helped her have more responsibilities and be more independent. She has learned a lot in the short time she has been here, and confident that this is the place for her.

To learn more about upgrade classes available, please visit: www.nasctf.org/courses/

When the initial battles in the Revolutionary War broke out in April 1775, few colonists desired complete independence from Great Britain, and those who did were considered radical.

By the middle of the following year, however, many more colonists had come to favor independence, thanks to growing hostility against Britain and the spread of revolutionary sentiments such as those expressed in the bestselling pamphlet â€œCommon Sense,â€ published by Thomas Paine in early 1776.

post_text:
Juneteenth is the oldest nationally celebrated commemoration of the ending of slavery in the United States. Dating back to 1865, it was on June 19th that the Union soldiers, led by Major General Gordon Granger, landed at Galveston, Texas with news that the war had ended and that the enslaved were now free. Note that this was two and a half years after President Lincolnâ€™s Emancipation Proclamation - which had become official January 1, 1863. The Emancipation Proclamation had little impact on the Texans due to the minimal number of Union troops to enforce the new Executive Order. However, with the surrender of General Lee in April of 1865, and the arrival of General Grangerâ€™s regiment, the forces were finally strong enough to influence and overcome the resistance.

Memorial Day, as Decoration Day gradually came to be known, originally honored only those lost while fighting in the Civil War. But during World War I the United States found itself embroiled in another major conflict, and the holiday evolved to commemorate American military personnel who died in all wars, including World War II, The Vietnam War, The Korean War and the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.

For decades, Memorial Day continued to be observed on May 30, the date Logan had selected for the first Decoration Day. But in 1968 Congress passed the Uniform Monday Holiday Act, which established Memorial Day as the last Monday in May in order to create a three-day weekend for federal employees; the change went into effect in 1971. The same law also declared Memorial Day a federal holiday.

Yesterday, we were fortunate enough to be able to help UMass Medical, Sturdy Memorial, and Countryside Health Care with a donation of personal protective equipment (PPE), which there is a critical shortage of nation wide. With support from our Superintendent, Steve Dockray, Facilities Director, Harry Takesian, Vocational Coordinator, Cathie Rebelo, and teachers from our high school and adult nursing programs we were able to make this happen.

We donated Clorox wipes, face masks, gowns, hand sanitizer, safety glasses and much, much more. Thank you to the faculty and staff who helped make this happen! ğŸ’™ğŸ’›ğŸ’™ğŸ’›

A special shout out to our instructors who initiated and helped make this happen (pictured): Patricia Munger, Tara Lane, Maureen Johnson, Suzanne Dodakian, and Lisa Ferrigno!

The Computer Information Systems (Grade 10) CyberPatriot Team #22, placed 3rd in the GOLD Tier State Round of the annual Youth Cyber Defense Competition! The National Youth Cyber Defense Competition puts teams of high school and middle school students in the position of newly hired IT professionals tasked with managing the network of a small company. Through a series of online competition rounds, teams are given a set of virtual operating systems and are tasked with finding and fixing cybersecurity vulnerabilities while maintaining critical services.
Congratulations on a job well done!

post_text: Today, the Automotive Technology Program was visited by three employees from Sullivan Tire and Auto Service. David G. Wilson, Brian Lamb, and Jacob Shutter gave a presentation on the latest in Automotive Diagnostic Equipment. During the visit Jacob, an ASE/World Class Technician (shown in picture) explained to the students how Sullivan Tire has kept up with the need for qualified Automotive Diagnosticians by showcasing one of six Mobile Diagnosing Vans. Jacob walked the 10th and 12th grade students through a day in his life by diagnosing a "bugged" shop vehicle. He explained how he travels all around the northeast to different shops diagnosing problem vehicles that other Automotive Technicians could not figure out, or do not have the proper equipment to fix. Sullivan Tire is now in the beginning steps in starting a co-op partnership with the Tri-County Automotive Technology Dept. Thank you Sullivan Tire & Auto Service!

MCAS Testing Schedule Spring 2020

Below is the testing calendar for Tri-County RVTHS for the spring of 2020. All students in grade 10 will take the state-required Massachusetts Comprehensive Assessment System (MCAS) tests for English Language Arts (ELA) and Mathematics. Additionally, all students in grade 9 and those grade 10 students who did not take the Biology MCAS last year will take the Biology MCAS test this spring. All three exams will be administered electronically and will be given in two sessions. All of these tests are untimed, although each session must be completed within the school day. Testing will begin first thing in the morning. It is very important for our students to beâ€¦ More

post_text: Culinary students Morgan Dahl (10), Dylan Peckham (12), and Kassidy Garrity (12), along with Culinary Arts instructor Nancy Haney competed at the second annual SkillsUSA MRE competition. The students used their creativity and culinary skills to transform MRE (Meals, Ready-to-Eat) into well-prepared, delicious meals. The Tri-County team competed against nineteen other high school teams, and they earned an overall bronze award. They also received a gold award for creativity. @ Natick, Massachusetts

post_text:
On January 15, 1929, Martin Luther King, Jr. is born in Atlanta, Georgia, the son of a Baptist minister. King received a doctorate degree in theology and in 1955 helped organize the first major protest of the African-American civil rights movement: the successful Montgomery Bus Boycott. Influenced by Mohandas Gandhi, he advocated civil disobedience and nonviolent resistance to segregation in the South. The peaceful protests he led throughout the American South were often met with violence, but King and his followers persisted, and the movement gained momentum.

On January 15, 1929, Martin Luther King, Jr. is born in Atlanta, Georgia, the son of a Baptist minister. King received a doctorate degree in theology and in 1955 helped organize the first major protest of the African-American civil rights movement: the successful Montgomery Bus Boycott. Influenced by Mohandas Gandhi, he advocated civil disobedience and nonviolent resistance to segregation in the South. The peaceful protests he led throughout the American South were often met with violence, but King and his followers persisted, and the movement gained momentum.

post_text: Today was a GREAT day for outdoor learning! Juniors in Ms. Hertel's Honors Trigonometry with Analytical Geometry course took advantage of the nice weather by using their knowledge of SOHCAHTOA to calculate the height of tall objects like the school building and the flag pole. They used an app on their phones to find the angle of elevation and a tape measure to find the distance on the ground to that object.
